df and du — the two questions about disk space.

When someone says "the disk is full," there are actually two completely different questions hiding in there, and they have two completely different tools. The first question is "how much space is on my filesystems?" That's df. The second is "what, specifically, is using space inside this directory?" That's du.

Start with df, disk free. It shows usage per mounted filesystem. df dash-h gives you human-readable sizes; df dash-h-capital-T also shows the filesystem type; and df dash-i shows inode usage instead of bytes. The columns are: Size, the total; Used; Avail, the space available to non-root users; Use-percent; and Mounted-on. Now, two surprises live in df output, and both bite people. The first is the five-percent root reserve: on ext4, by default, five percent of the filesystem is reserved for root. So df can say ninety-five percent used while a regular user already can't write a single byte. You can drop that reserve with tune2fs dash-m one. The second surprise is that inodes can run out before bytes do. Every file consumes one inode, and the number of inodes is fixed when the filesystem is created. So a pile of tiny files can exhaust the inodes while you still have gigabytes free. df dash-i reveals this, and the tell-tale sign is "No space left on device" even though there's clearly free space.

Now du, disk usage. It walks a directory tree and tells you how much space each thing takes. du dash-s-h gives one human-readable summary of a whole tree. du dash-h dash-dash-max-depth equals one goes just one level deep, which is the best way to find the big subdirectories. And the genuinely useful form: du dash-s-h on a glob, piped to sort dash-h, gives you everything sorted by size. The classic "find what's eating my disk" one-liner is du dash-s-h on the contents of a directory, piped to sort dash-h, piped to tail.

One last gotcha, and it's a favourite interview question. Sometimes df says the disk is full, but du says much less is used. The classic cause is a deleted-but-still-open file: a process is holding a file open, someone rm'd the file so it no longer shows up in du, but the kernel keeps the data on disk until that process closes it. You find these with lsof piped to grep deleted. And if you want a friendlier interactive tool, install ncdu, a terminal browser that makes finding big things very fast.
